    <p><strong>AA and KK: how to play before the Flop</strong></p>

    <ul>
      <li>With a Pair of Aces or Kings in an early position before the Flop. . .I would probably limp in with them (just call the Blind) hoping that somebody would raise it behind me so I could re raise.</li>
      <li>In a middle position if nobody in the early seats came in I would play them the same way. But, if somebody in the early seats did come in â€¦ Iâ€™d put in a raise with them (of about the size of the pot).</li>
      <li>In a late position, Iâ€™d obviously raise with them and hope that somebody trailed their hand around to me that is, slow-played their hand so they could re raise me. If they did Iâ€™d play back, of course, and might move in depending on the circumstances. If I did play back and got about half my money in the pot before the Flop with two Aces or two kings â€¦ thereâ€™d be no question that Iâ€™d get the rest of it in on the Flop regardless of what came on the turn. Nothing could stop me. If my opponent didnâ€™t set me in on the Flop â€¦ Iâ€™d move it all in myself</li>
      <li>A rare situation could exist where youâ€™d consider throwing away two Kings before the Flop when you got raised. Itâ€™s a hard hand to get away fromâ€¦but if a real tight player moved in on you a player you know to be so tight that he wouldnâ€™t make that kind of play unless he had two Aces then, you might want to throw them away. Of course, youâ€™d have to be almost certain about your man before youâ€™d do that. One way I make this rare decision is to put myself in my opponentâ€™s position. I ask myself if Iâ€™d re raise (if I were him) with two Queens (or less). If the answer is NO â€¦ Iâ€™d throw the two Kings away</li>
      <li>When you have two Kings and thereâ€™s a single Ace on the Flop â€¦ itâ€™s complete judgement as to whether or not you should go on with your hand. If you put your opponent on an Ace* â€¦ thatâ€™s the end of the pot right there. If not â€¦ you play your two Kings as if you had the best hand</li>
