      <li>Now, if Iâ€™m in a late seat â€¦ and somebody had trailed in in the early seats â€¦ I might go ahead and bet once. If I got called â€¦ I would immediately become defensive again with that hand. Anytime thereâ€™s three cards to a Straight or Flush, I play the hand with extreme caution</li>
      <li>You donâ€™t want to he drawing for a Flush when thereâ€™s a Pair on the Board. A man could have a Full house. And, you donâ€™t want to be drawing to a Straight when another man could have a Flush. If the Board comes three Hearts and youâ€™ve got an open end Straight draw you donâ€™t draw at that Straight. You throw your hand away. All the top players try to keep from ever getting their money in completely dead</li>
      <li>In brief â€¦ you donâ€™t give free cards where that free card could break you. If thereâ€™s a possible Straight or Flush draw on Board â€¦ you donâ€™t give a free card</li>
      <li>What it all boils down to is that with a Pair of Aces or Kings â€¦ youâ€™re waiting until you get kind of a cinch hand before you really play a big pot.</li>
      <li>Youâ€™re not looking to play a big pot where you might have only a small percentage the best of it or one where youâ€™re a big underdog</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>The play of a Pair of Aces or Kings in the hole: In most cases, I play them slowly (not slow play them). That is, I play them cautiously. This is contrary (to my general style of play and) to the way most people play them.
Most players feel that theyâ€™re so hard to come by that when they do get them
