  </li>
  <li>
    <p>As you continue to use my system of play, youâ€™ll discover the many advantages it has. The situation above is a good case in point. If the Flop was, say a 5-4-3 (giving me a Straight) â€¦ my opponent wouldâ€™ve let me know on the Flop whether or not he had a hand (Two-Pair or Trips). That is, if heâ€™s a good player he would. The reason why is because he wouldnâ€™t want another card to fall that would be one card off of a Straight. He knows if an Ace, Deuce, Six, or Seven comes on Fourth â€¦ heâ€™s going to have to give the pot up. He knows Iâ€™ll bet in that case whether or not I have the one card thatâ€™ll make the Straight.<br />
For that reason, all good Hold â€˜em players do most of their gambling on the Flopâ€¦ not on Fourth and Fifth Sts. Occasionally, youâ€™ll see a big pot played after the Flop â€¦ but, in the majority of cases, all the money usually goes in on the Flop. Thatâ€™s the reason the Flop is the most crucial point in the game</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>You should constantly be trying to get as much value for your hand as you can. And the way you do that is to bet</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>If youâ€™re going to callâ€¦ you might as well bet</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>If I made my hand early. ..Iâ€™m not going to try to sell him anything - Iâ€™m going to try to break him.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>If I made my hand late and I havenâ€™t been charged a lot of money to make it (like it was checked on the Flop and there was a small bet on Fourth and I make the nuts (in the end) â€¦ well, then Iâ€™m not going to try to break him -</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>because he probably wonâ€™t call a big bet. Then, Iâ€™d try to sell my hand for whatever I thought I could get for it</p>
  </li>
  <li><strong>TROUBLE HANDS (only when offsuit): Ace-Queen, King-Queen, Queen-Jack, Jack-Jack, Jack-Ten, Ace-Jack, King-Jack, Queen-Ten, Nine-Eight, Ace-Ten, King-Ten</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Two Important qualifications are that I donâ€™t consider the trouble hands borderline when:
        <ol>
          <li>theyâ€™re suited; and</li>
          <li>I get them In a short-handed game. As youâ€™ll learn, I define a shorthanded game as one with four players or less and In such a game the
 trouble hands are actually big hands</li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>Itâ€™s extremely hard to win a big pot with those hands (offsuited) when youâ€™ve called a raise. Theyâ€™re definitely trouble hands. Youâ€™re much more likely to lose a big pot with them than you are to win a big pot with them.
Even when I make a Pair with them on the Flop â€¦ I play them extremely cautiously - or about the same way Iâ€™d play when I had a Pair of Aces or Kings in the pocket</li>
      <li>For example, if I played a K-Q (offsuit) and the Board came K-4-2 â€¦ Iâ€™d be in a lot of trouble if the raiserâ€™s got one of the three hands Iâ€™ve assumed he might have. Heâ€™d have two Aces, three Kings or a Pair of Kings (like Iâ€™ve got) but heâ€™d have an Ace kicker. Or, if I played a 9-8 and the Flop was Q-J-10 â€¦ I still wouldnâ€™t be too excited about my hand - even though I turned a Straight. It would not only be the ignorant end of the Straight â€¦ but it would have an additional weakness because the high-end of the Straight would be made up by a very strong hand that everybody plays - namely, A-K. Something else you have to think about with the trouble hands is that itâ€™s not as easy to pick-up pots with them when you turn a Straight draw. Youâ€™ll remember that when I turn a Straight draw with small connecting cards, I play my hand real fast because I have two shots to win the pot. I can win the pot right on the Flop because, with small cards out there itâ€™s less likely anyone else turned a hand. And, if I do get called, Iâ€™ve still got a second shot to win it if I make my Straight. But, if I turn a Straight draw with a K-Q (say, the Flop is J-10-5) â€¦ itâ€™s highly likely somebodyâ€™s got a piece of that Flop - and Iâ€™m less likely to pick the pot up when I bet. So, I donâ€™t have two shots to win it anymore. The same kind of reasoning applies to the times when you might turn the top Pair and a Straight draw with a K-Q when the Flop is Q-J-10. Itâ€™s not even a good hand then because you might be dead (as you would be with a 9-8) when somebody has an A-K. The best you could be drawing for would be a split</li>
      <li>Even when you turn a very good hand like Two-Pair or Trips â€¦ you could be in jeopardy. If the Flop was K-K-2â€¦ you could once again be in big trouble with K-Q when someoneâ€™s got A-K. The difference here is that you probably wonâ€™t be able to get away from your hand and youâ€™ll have to go ahead and lose a lot of money. The important point to remember about the trouble hands is when you do get a Flop to them you donâ€™t want to get heavily involved. You should just try to play the pot as cheaply as possible</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Trash &amp; Garbage Hands</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>With the exception of an Ace or a King with any suited card â€¦ I consider any hand I havenâ€™t already discussed to be a trash hand</li>
      <li>Other than the exceptional situations trash hands are just not playable</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Ace or a King with any suited card</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>An Ac-8c or a Kh-4h are hands that I put in the same category as the small connecting cards and I play them approximately the same way. For example, if the Flop was 9h-6c-2c, and I had the Ac-8c â€¦ Iâ€™d have a Flush draw and an overcard. If I was in the pot against two Queens â€¦ Iâ€™d be about even-money to win it. So Iâ€™d play my hand in that situation like I would with two small connecting cards that were suited (say the 9c-8c). That is, Iâ€™d play it fast â€¦ and try to win the pot on the Flop because, once again, Iâ€™d have two shots to win it. However, the trouble hands suited or offsuit should be played the came way - slowly - unless you Flop a Flush or a Flush draw. Then, you can show some Speed. But thatâ€™s where I draw the line - with an Ace or a King and another suited card. After it passed the Ace and King â€¦ if the two cards donâ€™t connect - even if theyâ€™re suited - I consider them trash hands. Hands like a Qh-4h or Js-6s are trash. Naturally, hands with non-connecting and offsuit cards such as Jh-5c, 1Os-3d, 9c-4h are obviously garbage. But, so are the offsuit hands such as K-9, Q-8, J-7, 10-6, 9-5, 8-4, 7-3 and 6-2 that a lot of people play because you can turn a Straight with them. I donâ€™t play those hands because if I got the best Flop I could to them (outside of a Full House) â€¦ I could get broke with them by running into a bigger Straight. Consequently, I never play a hand when I have the top and bottom cards of a Straight - except when Iâ€™m in position</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>In a short-handed game, the trouble hands all become playable from almost any position. Also, position is probably the most important thing in a short-handed game. The reason thatâ€™s so is because you get to look at more cards and have to play more hands than you would in a Ring game. You also play your position more than your cards in a short-handed game. When your gameâ€™s down to four-handed, you need a better hand in the first two positions than you need in the last two. When you raise on the Button, the other man has to act first (on the Flop) and that puts him at a big disadvantage. Itâ€™s a great equalizer when the other man has to act on his hand first</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>So, in a short-handed game, youâ€™d play your position along the same theories I discussed in a full game - except the values of the hands go up a few notches. The  trouble hands become better hands because you donâ€™t figure to be up against A-A, K-K or A-K nearly as often as you might in a Ring game</p>
  </li>
  <li>You simply play more in line with a big-card theory in a short-handed game. I mean, the bigger your cards are â€¦ the better hand youâ€™ll have. For instance, two Aces or two Kings is just a mountain in a short-handed game â€¦ and you could play them real fast. But, in a Ring game, you might play either hand a lot slower because there could be a lot of people taking a Turn to beat those big Pairs. That wouldnâ€™t be the case in a short-handed game. Consequently, theyâ€™re much more valuable hands than they are in a Ring game. What youâ€™re trying to catch in a short-handed game is big cards in position</li>
</ul>

